The best rationale for selecting a comparison group that had chest x-rays is to minimize ascertainment bias.

Ascertainment bias occurs when the method of identifying or recording outcomes (such as disease diagnosis) differs between groups, leading to inaccurate or skewed results. In this study, both the mesothelioma cases and the non-cases had chest x-rays, ensuring that the diagnosis of mesothelioma was based on the same set of imaging data. This makes it more likely that the diagnosis was accurately and consistently recorded across groups, reducing the risk of bias due to differences in how health records were obtained or interpreted.

Therefore, including a comparison group with chest x-rays ensures that the diagnosis of mesothelioma was ascertained in a uniform manner, improving the validity of the study findings.

The answer is (C)
